The '''Yucatan jay''' ('''''Cyanocorax yucatanicus''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Corvidae]], the crows and their allies. It is native to the [[Yucatán Peninsula]] where its habitats are subtropical or tropical dry forest, plantations and cleared areas at altitudes up to {{convert|250|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Adults are about {{convert|30|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, black, with blue wings, mantle, and tail, black bills, yellow eye rings and legs. Immature birds have yellow bills. This is a common species of jay with a wide range and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has rated its conservation status as being of "[[least-concern species|least concern]]".

==Taxonomy==
The Yucatan jay was first described by the naturalist [[Alphonse Dubois]] in 1875. It originally places in the genus ''[[Cyanocitta]]'', and was given the [[binomial nomenclature|scientific name]] ''Cyanocitta yucatanica''.{{sfnp|Dubois|1875|p=797}} It is now placed by the genus ''[[Cyanocorax]]'', which was introduced by the German zoologist [[Friedrich Boie]] in 1826, as ''Cyanocorax yucatanicus''.{{sfnp|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}}{{sfnp|Boie|1826|loc=Col 975}} In 1934, ornithologist [[Carl Eduard Hellmayr]] reorganized the genus ''Cyanocorax'' and split it into four [[subgenus|subgenera]]. The Yucatan jay was placed into the subgenus ''Cissilopha'' as ''Cissilopha yucatanica''.{{sfnp|Hellmayr|1934|p=39}} This is now considered a synonym for the Yucatan jay.{{sfnp|Lepage}} 

When Hellmayr created the subgenus ''Cissilopha'', he placed the [[bushy-crested jay]], the [[San Blas jay]], and the [[purplish-backed jay]] into it along with the Yucatan jay based on their similar plumage.{{sfnp|Bonaccorso|Peterson|Navarro-Sigüenza|Fleischer|2010|p=898}} This relationship was confirmed by a 2010 [[mitochondrial DNA]] study, which showed that these four species were closely related. The Yucatan jay is [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] to a [[sister group]] formed by the San Blas jay and the Purplish-backed jay.{{sfnp|Bonaccorso|Peterson|Navarro-Sigüenza|Fleischer|2010|p=902}}

