The Yucatan jay has two recognized [[subspecies]].{{sfnp|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}}
*''C. yucataniucs yucatanicus'': Found in [[Yucatán]], [[Quintana Roo]], and [[Campeche]] (except the southwest portion) in southeastern Mexico; [[Petén Department|Petén]] in northern Guatemala; and northern Belize.{{sfnp|Duvall|Kirwan|2020|loc=Systematics}}
*''C. yucatanicus rivularis'': Found in [[Tabasco]] and southwestern Campeche in southeastern Mexico.{{sfnp|Duvall|Kirwan|2020|loc=Systematics}} Somewhat larger, and with a silvery tinge to the blue {{Birdgloss|upperparts}}.{{sfnp|Madge|Burn|1994|p=82}}

==Description==
The adult Yucatan jay has a black head, {{Birdgloss|nape}}, and {{Birdgloss|underparts}}. The back, wings, and tail are a sharp blue colour. It has black [[iris (anatomy)|irises]], black eye rings, a black beak, and yellow legs and feet. There is no difference between the sexes.{{sfnp|Madge|Burn|1994|pp=81–82}}

===Moults===
[[File:Cyanocorax yucatanicus 161742222 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Juveniles have distinct white heads and bodies, but this fades within a few weeks of fledging]]
The Yucatan jay has several distinct [[plumage]]s throughout its life cycle. Juvenile Yucatan jays have a white head, body, and tail tip. The back is a soft blue, and the wings and tail are a soft grey, aside from the outer [[rectrice]]s which are white. The beak, legs, and feet are a soft yellow tinged with pink. The inside of the beak is white and the irises are dark brown.{{sfnp|Hardy|1973|p=85}} These features start to fade a few weeks after they [[fledge]].{{sfnp|Madge|Burn|1994|p=82}} At this point, the legs, feet, beak, and eye ring become more distinctly yellow. The prebasic [[moult]] also begins at this point, with the white head and body feathers being replaced with black ones.{{sfnp|Hardy|1973|p=85}} 

[[File:Cyanocorax yucatanicus 339619349.jpg|thumb|right|The yellow beak and eye rings begin to fade to black within their second year]]
During the first year, the Yucatan jay has an entirely black head and body. The legs, feet, and eye rings remain yellow. The inside of the beak remains white, but takes on a glaucous tone. The wings become bluer, and the tail becomes a purplish blue colour. The back and tail turn a deeper grey, and the rectrices are tipped with white. In June or August, the bill may start to develop dark patches, while remaining overall yellow. In September, the dark patches expand further.{{sfnp|Hardy|1973|pp=85–86}}

In its second year, the Yucatan jay's plumage is the same as that of the adult. The beak is still mottled, and by March it is primarily black with only some yellow marks, becoming entirely black within the second year. The legs and feet remain yellow. The eye ring is still distinctive of age, with some black marks appearing on the otherwise yellow flesh. By the third year, this eye ring is almost entirely black. The darkening of the beak and eye ring usually progress at the same rate. The inside of the beak starts to darken at this point as well. Any trace of yellow on both the beak and eye rings are gone by January of the third year. In the fourth year and later, the Yucatan jay has reached its full adult plumage.{{sfnp|Hardy|1973|p=82}}

===Measurements===
The Yucatan jay is a medium sized jay, averaging {{cvt|31–33|cm|in}} long.{{sfnp|Madge|Burn|1994|p=81}} There is some variation in size between the sexes. The average wing length for adults is {{cvt|141|mm|in}} for males and {{cvt|139.5|mm|in}} for females, and the average tail length is {{cvt|142.5|mm|in}} for males and {{cvt|141.5|mm|in}} for females. Both sexes have an average beak length of {{cvt|22.5|mm|in}}, an average beak depth of {{cvt|12.7|mm|in}}, and average tarsus length of {{cvt|41|mm|in}}, and an average middle toe length of {{cvt|25|mm|in}}.{{sfnp|Ridgway|1904|p=315}} The male is also slightly heavier, weighing {{cvt|114.4–127.8|g|oz}} compared to the female who weighs {{cvt|105.4–121|g|oz}}.{{sfnp|Duvall|Kirwan|2020|loc=Plumaes, Molts, and Structure}}

===Similar species===
The Yucatan jay is visually unique within its range, with no similar species. Outside of its range, it is similar to the [[San Blas jay]], the [[purplish-backed jay]], and the [[bushy-crested jay]]. All three have a yellow iris whereas the Yucatan jay has a black iris, and are a brighter shade of blue on their upperparts.{{sfnp|Duvall|Kirwan|2020|loc=Identification}}{{sfnp|Madge|Burn|1994|p=82}}

==Range and habitat==
The Yucatan jay is found primarily in the [[Yucatán Peninsula]], which comprises the northern part of the nation of [[Belize]]; [[Guatemala]]'s northern El Petén Department; and the [[Mexico|Mexican]] states of [[Yucatán]], [[Quintana Roo]], and [[Campeche]]. It is also present in parts of the neighbouring states of [[Chiapas]] and [[Tabasco]].{{sfnp|BirdLife International|2020}} 

The [[habitat]]s of the Yucatan Jay vary slightly depending on the subspecies. The nominate species (''C. y. yucatanicus'') is found most often in both [[Yucatán moist forests|humid]] and [[Yucatán dry forests|scrubby]] forests, but can also be found in coastal scrub. ''C. y. rivularis'', found in the southwest portion of the Yucatan peninsula, can be found in almost any type of forest. It can also be found in [[Belizian pine forests|pine forests]] and swamps, however it is not common in these areas. Both subspecies can be found at elevations up to {{cvt|500|m|ft}}.{{sfnp|Madge|Burn|1994|p=82}}{{sfnp|Raitt|Hardy|1976|p=530}} The Yucatan jay is [[Bird migration|non-migratory]].{{sfnp|Duvall|Kirwan|2020|loc=Movements and Migration}}

==Status==
The Yucatan jay is a common species throughout most of its wide range. Its population is considered stable, and as of 2020 there are an estimated 50,000–500,000 mature individuals in the wild. No particular threats have been identified, and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has rated its conservation status as being of  [[least-concern species|least concern]].{{sfnp|BirdLife International|2020}}

